diff:1669491292:1669491292:=1,104d0%0a%3c (:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0a%3c Status: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!{$:Category}]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Loanwords in Japanese%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: heidit%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Japanese is a language with an abundance of loanwords. %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Japanese is a language with an abundance of loanwords. %0a%3c %0a%3c According to the categorization by Mark Irwin in his book “Loanwords in Japanese” (2011), Japanese vocabulary are mainly constituted of these strata: native, Sino-Japanese (that come from China mainly during the Han Dynasty) and foreign (pp. 24–27). This wiki entry will be mainly exploring the last stratum. %0a%3c %0a%3c The borrowing from European languages mainly happened during the Meiji Restoration in the late 1800s (Irwin, 2011, p.42). Eagerly craving for modernization, Japanese leaders decided to learn from Western scientific and cultural knowledge to boost its own growth and development. What came along with the knowledge was the specific words related to those areas, some of which are used in daily lives and others are technical vocabulary in professional fields.%0a%3c %0a%3c For example, Japanese loanwords from German are mainly contributed of medical, physics, and political words. “エネルギー” (pronounced as “enerugii”, which means “energy”) comes from the German word “die Energie”.%0a%3c %0a%3c Some words combine western words (e.g., “def Dopplereffekt”) with other strata (e.g, 効果, “kouka”, meaning “effect”), as exemplified by “ドップラー効果” (pronounced as “doppuraakouka”, means “the Doppler Effect”).%0a%3c %0a%3c Other examples of loanwords from German include “リュック” (pronunciation= “ryukku”, German=“der Rucksack”, meaning “rucksack”), “アルバイト” (pronunciation=”arubaito”, German = “die Arbeit”, meaning “work” in German but “part-time job” in Japanese), and “テーゼ” (pronunciation= “teeze”, German = “die These”) (Irwin, 2011, p.52).%0a%3c %0a%3c There are also many loanwords from other countries. For those from French, there are more of the dining and abstract words, like “クロワッサン” (pronounced as “kurowassann”, meaning “croissant”) and “グランプリ” (pronounced as “gurannpuri”, meaning “grand prix”) (Irwin, 2011, p. 49). Those from English include many words we use in our daily lives, like “テレビ” (“terebi”, meaning “television”) and “ページ” (“peeji”, meaning “page”) (Irwin, 2011, p. 59). %0a%3c %0a%3c What’s also interesting is that some words don’t directly borrow the pronunciation, but instead borrow the meaning. For example, the word for “oxygen” is Japanese is “酸素(Sannso)” (酸= “sour”, 素= “stuff”). This is because when oxygen was first discovered, it was thought as the source of sourness. This corresponds to the Dutch word “zuurstof” (zuur= “sour”, stof= “stuff”) (Kyoko, 2008). But this may not be considered a loanword by many. %0a%3c %0a%3c In short, most of the loanwords are nouns, and they are borrowed because of the new “things” that comes into peoples’ lives. It’s enjoyable to see the connection between languages and specific historical developments.  %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Reference%0a%3c [1] Irwin, M. (2011). Loanwords in Japanese. John Benjamins Publishing Company. %0a%3c [2] Kyoko, I. (2008, November 7). 日本最初の化学書. もうひとつの学芸員室. http://www.eisai.co.jp/museum/curator/column/081107c.html%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c 